  "prompt": "What technologies were used to build Justickets.com?",
  "response": "As of my last knowledge update in October 2021, specific information about the technologies used to build Justickets.com was not publicly available. However, websites like Justickets, which is an online ticketing platform, typically utilize a combination of various technologies for their development. Common technologies used in similar platforms include:\n\n1. **Frontend Technologies**:\n   - **HTML/CSS**: For structuring and styling web pages.\n   - **JavaScript Frameworks**: Such as React, Angular, or Vue.js for building interactive user interfaces.\n\n2. **Backend Technologies**:\n   - **Server-side Languages**: Such as Node.js, Python (Django or Flask), Ruby on Rails, or PHP for handling server-side logic.\n   - **Web Frameworks**: That facilitate building web applications more efficiently.\n\n3. **Databases**:\n   - **SQL Databases**: Such as MySQL or PostgreSQL for structured data storage.\n   - **NoSQL Databases**: Like MongoDB for handling unstructured data.\n\n4. **Payment Gateways**:\n   - Integration with payment processing services like Stripe, PayPal, or Razorpay for handling transactions securely.\n\n5. **Cloud Services**:\n   - Hosting and storage solutions from providers like AWS, Google Cloud, or Microsoft Azure.\n\n6. **APIs**:\n   - RESTful or GraphQL APIs to facilitate communication between the frontend and backend.\n\n7. **DevOps Tools**:\n   - Use of Docker, Kubernetes, or CI/CD pipelines for deployment and scalability.\n\n8. **Content Management Systems (CMS)**:\n   - For managing content if the site includes blogs or articles.\n\nFor the most accurate and up-to-date information, I recommend checking Justickets.com directly, looking at their technical documentation (if available), or using web technology analysis tools like BuiltWith or Wappalyzer.",
